	(29, 0, 'Insufficient particularity', 'Objection, this Request is insufficiently particularized.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 19.30, citing Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2031.030, subd. (c)(1).', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(30, 0, 'Irrelevant to the Subject Matter', 'Objection, this Interrogatory is irrelevant to the subject matter of this case.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 18.35, citing Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2017.010.', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(31, 0, 'Irrelevant to the Subject Matter', 'Objection, this Request is irrelevant to the subject matter of this case.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 18.35, citing Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2017.010.', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(32, 0, 'Irrelevant to the Subject Matter', 'Objection, this Request is irrelevant to the subject matter of this case.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 19.30, citing Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2017.010.', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(33, 0, 'Legal reasoning/theory', 'Objection, this Interrogatory improperly intrudes into the party&apos;s legal reasoning or theory.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 18.35, citing Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2030.010, subd. (b) and <i>Sav-On Drugs, Inc. v. Superior Court</i> (1975) 15 Cal.3d 1.', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(34, 0, 'Non-specific objection', 'If an objection is made to an Interrogatory or part of one, the specific ground for the objection shall be set forth clearly in the response. Code Civ.Proc., § 2030.240, subd. (b).', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(35, 0, 'Not full and complete', 'Objection, this Request is not full and complete in and of itself.', 'Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2033.060, subd. (d).', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(36, 0, 'Oppressive', 'Objection, this Interrogatory is oppressive.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 18.35, citing <i>West Pico Furniture Co. of Los Angeles v. Superior Court In and For Los Angeles County</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 407, 417.\r\n\r\n<bNotes</b>\r\n&quot;To support an objection of oppression there must be some showing either of an intent to create an unreasonable burden or that the ultimate effect of the burden is incommensurate with the result sought.&quot; <i>West Pico Furniture Co. of Los Angeles v. Superior Court In and For Los Angeles County</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 407, 417.', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(37, 0, 'Oppressive', 'Objection, this Request is oppressive.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 22.30.\r\n\r\n<b>Notes</b>\r\n&quot;To support an objection of oppression there must be some showing either of an intent to create an unreasonable burden or that the ultimate effect of the burden is incommensurate with the result sought.&quot; <i>West Pico Furniture Co. of Los Angeles v. Superior Court In and For Los Angeles County</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 407, 417.', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(38, 0, 'Oppressive', 'Objection, this Request is oppressive.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 19.30, citing Mead Reinsurance Co. v Superior Court (1986) 188 CA3d 313, 321.\r\n\r\n<b>Notes</b>\r\n&quot;To support an objection of oppression there must be some showing either of an intent to create an unreasonable burden or that the ultimate effect of the burden is incommensurate with the result sought.&quot; <i>West Pico Furniture Co. of Los Angeles v. Superior Court In and For Los Angeles County</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 407, 417.', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(39, 0, 'Privacy', 'Objection, this Interrogatory improperly invades privacy rights protected by art I, § 1 of the California Constitution and the First Amendment to U.S. Constitution.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 18.35.\r\n\r\n<b>Notes</b>\r\nSome courts used to require the party seeking private information to justify the need for it. Recently, however, the California Supreme Court reversed the burden. Now, &quot;the party asserting a privacy right must establish a legally protected privacy interest, an objectively reasonable expectation of privacy in the given circumstances, and a threatened intrusion that is serious.&quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 552.', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(40, 0, 'Privacy', 'Objection, this Request improperly invades privacy rights protected by art I, § 1 of the California Constitution and the First Amendment to U.S. Constitution.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 22.30.\r\n\r\n<b>Notes</b>\r\nSome courts used to require the party seeking private information to justify the need for it. Recently, however, the California Supreme Court reversed the burden. Now, &quot;the party asserting a privacy right must establish a legally protected privacy interest, an objectively reasonable expectation of privacy in the given circumstances, and a threatened intrusion that is serious.&quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 552.', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(41, 0, 'Privacy', 'Objection, this Request improperly invades privacy rights protected by art I, § 1 of the California Constitution and the First Amendment to U.S. Constitution.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 19.30.\r\n\r\n<b>Notes</b>\r\nSome courts used to require the party seeking private information to justify the need for it. Recently, however, the California Supreme Court reversed the burden. Now, &quot;the party asserting a privacy right must establish a legally protected privacy interest, an objectively reasonable expectation of privacy in the given circumstances, and a threatened intrusion that is serious.&quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 552.', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(42, 0, 'Public record', 'Objection, there is no duty to search out matters of public record.', 'Weil & Brown, Cal. Practice Guide&#58; Civil Procedure Before Trial (The Rutter Group 2020) &#182; 8:1063, citing <i>Bunnell v. Sup.Ct.</i> (1967) 254 CA2d 720, 723-724. See also, Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 18.35, citing Code Civ.Proc., § 2030.220, subd. (c).', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(43, 0, 'Seeks Documents', 'Objection, this Interrogatory improperly seeks documents.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 18.35.\r\n\r\n<b>Notes</b>\r\nNo provision relating to interrogatories authorizes compelling production of a document or thing.', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(44, 0, 'Subparts', 'Objection, this Interrogatory improperly contains subparts.', 'Code Civ.Proc., &sect;&sect; 2030.060, subd. (f), 2033.710.\r\n\r\n<b>Notes</b>\r\nThe prohibition on subparts does not appear to prohibit their use in definitions.', 0, 0, 1, 0, 0),
	(45, 0, 'Subparts', 'Objection, this Request improperly contains subparts.', 'Code Civ.Proc., &sect;&sect; 2033.060, subd. (f), 2033.710.\r\n\r\n<b>Notes</b>\r\nThe prohibition on subparts in Special Interrogatories does not prohibit their use in definitions.', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(46, 0, 'Taxpayer privilege', 'Tax returns, including all documents required to be attached to a return such as W-2 forms, are privileged.', '<i>Webb v. Standard Oil Co. of Cal.</i> (1957) 49 Cal.2d 509, 513. &quot;Tax returns&quot; includes all documents that &quot;are required to be attached to a taxpayer&apos;s state and federal income tax returns&quot; including W-2 forms. <i>Brown v. Superior Court</i> (1977) 71 Cal.App.3d 141, 143-144.', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(47, 0, 'Trade Secrets', 'Objection, this Interrogatory improperly seeks information protected by the Trade Secrets privilege.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 18.35, citing Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2030.240, subd. (b).\r\n\r\n<b>Notes</b>\r\nThis applies only if the Trade Secrets privilege has been asserted.', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(48, 0, 'Trade Secrets', 'Objection, this Request improperly seeks information protected by the Trade Secrets privilege.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 22.30, citing Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2033.230, subd. (b).\r\n\r\n<b>Notes</b>\r\nThis applies only if the Trade Secrets privilege has been asserted.', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(49, 0, 'Trade Secrets', 'Objection, this Request improperly seeks information protected by the Trade Secrets privilege.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 19.30, citing Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2031.240, subd. (b)(2).\r\n\r\n<b>Notes</b>\r\nThis applies only if the Trade Secrets privilege has been asserted.', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(50, 0, 'Unduly burdensome', 'Objection, this Interrogatory is unduly burdensome.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 18.35. See also, <i>West Pico Furniture Co. of Los Angeles v. Superior Court In and For Los Angeles County</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 407, 417 [&quot;The objection based upon burden must be sustained by evidence showing the quantum of work required.&quot;].', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(51, 0, 'Unduly burdensome', 'Objection, this Request is unduly burdensome.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 19.30. See also, <i>West Pico Furniture Co. of Los Angeles v. Superior Court In and For Los Angeles County</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 407, 417 [&quot;The objection based upon burden must be sustained by evidence showing the quantum of work required.&quot;].', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(52, 0, 'Unduly burdensome', 'Objection, this Request is unduly burdensome.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 22.30. See also, <i>West Pico Furniture Co. of Los Angeles v. Superior Court In and For Los Angeles County</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 407, 417 [&quot;The objection based upon burden must be sustained by evidence showing the quantum of work required.&quot;].', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(53, 0, 'Unreasonable place', 'Objection, this Request specifies an unreasonable place for performing the activity.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 19.30, citing Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2031.030, subd. (c)(3).', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(54, 0, 'Unreasonable time', 'Objection, this Request specifies an unreasonable time for performing the activity.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 19.30, citing Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2031.030, subd. (c)(2).', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(55, 0, 'Vague', '&quot;Vague&quot; is a nuisance objection and a party relying upon it is subject to sanction.', '<i>Standon Co. v. Superior Court</i> (1990) 225 Cal.App.3d 898, 901.', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(56, 0, 'Vague', 'Vague is not an approved objection to a Request for Admission.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019) &sect; 22.30.', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(57, 0, 'Vague', 'Vague is not an approved objection to an Interrogatory.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019) &sect; 18.35.', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(58, 0, 'Vague/unintelligible', 'Objection, vague or unintelligible.', 'Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019) &sect; 19.30.\r\n\r\n<b>Notes</b>\r\nThis is only a valid objection if ambiguity precludes an intelligent reply. <i>Cembrook v Superior Court</i> (1961) 56 C2d 423, 430.', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),

	(59, 1, 'Already asked via other discovery devices', 'Your objection is meritless. A party may use multiple &quot;discovery methods for obtaining the same documents or information.&quot; <i>Carter v. Superior Court</i> (1990) 218 Cal.App.3d 994, 997.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(60, 1, 'Ambiguous', '&quot;Ambiguity&quot; is not sufficient grounds for refusal to answer unless the request is so ambiguous that the responding party cannot in good faith frame an intelligent reply. <i>Cembrook v. Superior Court In and For City and County of San Francisco</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 423, 428.', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(61, 1, 'Ambiguous', '&quot;Ambiguous&quot; is a nuisance objection and a party relying upon it, as you&apos;ve done, is &quot;subject to sanction.&quot; <i>Standon Co. v. Superior Court</i> (1990) 225 Cal.App.3d 898, 901.', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 1),
	(62, 1, 'Argumentative', '&quot;Argumentative&quot; is an objection to the form of the question. It is appropriate only at deposition, not for written discovery. Rylaarsdam et al., California Practice Guide&#58; Civil Procedure Before Trial (The Rutter Group 2019) &sect; 8:721-8:722.', '', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(63, 1, 'Assumes facts not in evidence', '&quot;Assumes facts not in evidence&quot; is only valid at an oral deposition; it is not a proper objection to written discovery. <i>West Pico Furniture Co. of Los Angeles v. Superior Court In and For Los Angeles County</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 407, 421.', '', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(64, 1, 'Attorney Work product&#58; Evidence', 'Nonderivative material, evidentiary in nature, is not work product. Examples of such material include the identity and location of physical evidence or witnesses. <i>Coito v. Superior Court</i> (2012) 54 Cal.4th 480, 489.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(65, 1, 'Attorney work product&#58; Witness statements', '&quot;A statement independently prepared by a witness does not become protected work product simply upon its transmission to an attorney.&quot; <i>Coito v. Superior Court</i> (2012) 54 Cal.4th 480, 494. &quot;Such statements neither reflect an attorney&apos;s evaluation of the case nor constitute derivative material, and therefore are neither absolute nor qualified work product.&apos;&quot; <i>Id.</i> at 500.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(66, 1, 'Attorney-client privilege/Work product', 'An objection based upon the Attorney Client privilege and/or Work Product requires the respondent to &quot;provide sufficient factual information for other parties to evaluate the merits of that claim, including, if necessary, a privilege log.&quot; Code Civ.Proc., § 2031.240(c)(1).', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(67, 1, 'Attorney-client privilege/Work product&#58; Document containing privileged information', '&quot;The <i>existence</i> of a document containing privileged information is not privileged.&quot; <i>Hernandez v. Superior Court</i> (2003) 112 Cal.App.4th 285, 293, emphasis in original.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(68, 1, 'Attorney-client privilege/work product&#58; Refusal to provide responsive documents', 'Where an objection is based upon privilege or work product, &quot;the response shall provide sufficient factual information for other parties to evaluate the merits of that claim, including, if necessary, a privilege log.&quot; Code Civ. Proc., &sect; 2031.240(c)(1). The party asserting the privilege has &quot;the initial burden of proving the preliminary facts to show the privilege applies.&quot; <i>Lopez v. Watchtower Bible & Tract Society of New York, Inc.</i> (2016) 246 Cal.App.4th 566, 596. And a party that fails to produce &quot;a privilege log or identify any specific confidential communications&quot; fails to meet its burden. <i>Ibid.</i>', NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
	(69, 1, 'Attorney-client privilege/Work product&#58; Sub rosa surveillance', 'Video evidence of an opposing party is not protected by the attorney-client privilege or work product doctrine. It is discoverable. <i>Suezaki v. Superior Court of Santa Clara County</i> (1962) 58 Cal.2d 166, 176-177.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(70, 1, 'Attorney-client privilege&#58; Communications with attorney', 'The attorney-client privilege does not embrace matters otherwise unprivileged merely because the client has communicated those matters to his attorney. <i>Green & Shinee v. Superior Court</i> (2001) 88 Cal.App.4th 532, 537.\r\n\r\nSee also, <i>Grand Lake Drive In, Inc. v. Superior Court In and For Alameda County</i> (1960) 179 Cal.App.2d 122, 127 [&quot;A litigant cannot silence a witness by having him reveal his knowledge to the litigant&apos;s attorney.&quot;]', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(71, 1, 'Attorney-client privilege&#58; Identify of witnesses; location of documents', 'The Attorney-client privilege does not extend to individuals who are no more than witnesses to the matter at issue in the litigation. <i>2,022 Ranch v. Superior Court</i> (2003) 113 Cal.App.4th 1377, 1388, disapproved of on unrelated grounds by <i>Costco Wholesale Corp. v. Superior Court</i> (2009) 47 Cal.4th 725. See also, <i>Coito v. Superior Court</i> (2012) 54 Cal.4th 480, 489 [the identity and location of physical evidence or witnesses is not work product.]\r\n', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(72, 1, 'Burdensome', '&quot;Burdensome&quot; is not a valid objection to a Request for Admission. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 22.30. Additionally, the objection must be sustained by evidence showing the quantum of work required. <i>West Pico Furniture Co. of Los Angeles v. Superior Court In and For Los Angeles County</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 407, 417. Since you&apos;ve failed to provide such evidence, your objection is invalid.', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(73, 1, 'Burdensome', '&quot;Burdensome&quot; is not a valid objection to a Request for Production of Documents. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), &sect; 19.30. Additionally, the objection must be sustained by evidence showing the quantum of work required. <i>West Pico Furniture Co. of Los Angeles v. Superior Court In and For Los Angeles County</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 407, 417. Since you&apos;ve failed to provide such evidence, your objection is invalid.', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(74, 1, 'Burdensome', '&quot;Burdensome&quot; is not a valid objection to an Interrogatory. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), § 18.35. Additionally, &quot;The objection based upon burden must be sustained by evidence showing the quantum of work required.&quot; <i>West Pico Furniture Co. of Los Angeles v. Superior Court In and For Los Angeles County</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 407, 417. Since you&apos;ve failed to provide such evidence, your objection is invalid.', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(75, 1, 'Calls for a legal opinion/conclusion', '&apos;Calls for a legal opinion or conclusion&apos; is not a valid objection to a Request for Admission. &quot;When a party is served with a request for admission concerning a legal question properly raised in the pleadings he cannot object simply by asserting that the request calls for a conclusion of law. He should make the admission if he is able to do so and does not in good faith intend to contest the issue at trial, thereby &apos;setting at rest a triable issue.&apos; Otherwise he should set forth in detail the reasons why he cannot truthfully admit or deny the request.&quot; <i>Burke v. Superior Court</i> (1969) 71 Cal.2d 276, 282, internal citations omitted. See also, <i>Cembrook v. Superior Court In and For City and County of San Francisco</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 423, 429 [&quot;calls for a legal conclusion&quot; is not a valid objection.].', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(76, 1, 'Calls for a legal opinion/conclusion', '&quot;Calls for a legal opinion or conclusion&quot; is not a valid objection to a Request for Production of Documents. Cal. Judges Benchbook &sect; 19.30.', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(77, 1, 'Calls for a legal opinion/conclusion', '&quot;Calls for a legal opinion or conclusion&quot; is not a valid objection to an Interrogatory. &quot;An interrogatory is not objectionable because an answer to it involves an opinion or contention that relates to fact or the application of law to fact, or would be based on information obtained or legal theories developed in anticipation of litigation or in preparation for trial.&quot; Code Civ.Proc., § 2030.010, subd. (b).', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(78, 1, 'Calls for a narrative', '&quot;Calls for a narrative&quot; is only appropriate at a deposition, not for written discovery. Cal. Judges Benchbook &sect; 19.30. See also, Rylaarsdam et al., California Practice Guide&#58; Civil Procedure Before Trial (The Rutter Group 2019) &sect; 8:721-8:722.', '', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(79, 1, 'Calls for speculation', '&quot;Calls for speculation&quot; is an objection to the form of the question. It is appropriate only at a deposition, not for written discovery. Rylaarsdam et al., California Practice Guide&#58; Civil Procedure Before Trial (The Rutter Group 2019) § 8:721-8:722.', '', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(80, 1, 'CCP § 1985.6', 'Your objection that the Interrogatory fails to comply with Code of Civil Procedure section 1985.6 is nonsensical. This isn’t a deposition and the information isn’t being sought via a subpoena dues tecum.', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(81, 1, 'Compound', '&quot;Compound&quot; is not a valid objection to a Form Interrogatory. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery &sect; 18.36.', '', 1, 1, 0, 0, 0),
	(82, 1, 'Compound', '&quot;Compound&quot; is not an approved objection to a Request for Production of Documents. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery &sect; 19.30.', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(83, 1, 'Compound', '&quot;Compound&quot; is only an appropriate objection at an oral deposition, it is not appropriate for Interrogatories. <i>West Pico Furniture Co. of Los Angeles v. Superior Court In and For Los Angeles County</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 407.\r\n\r\n', '<b>WARNING&#58;</b> This opinion is in derogation of Code of Civil Procedure section 2030.060, subdivision (f).', 0, 0, 1, 0, 0),
	(84, 1, 'Cumulative/duplicative', '&quot;Cumulative and duplicative&quot; apply only to a Motion to Compel Further Response to a Request for Production of Electronically Stored Information. Code Civ.Proc., 2031.310 subd. (g)(2) and oral depositions Code Civ.Proc., 2025.480 subd. (g)(2).', '', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(85, 1, 'Definitions are compound/conjunctive/disjunctive', 'Definitions are not prohibited from including compound, conjunctive, or disjunctive language. Code Civ.Proc., § 2030.060.', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(86, 1, 'Definitions are compound/conjunctive/disjunctive', 'Definitions are not prohibited from including compound, conjunctive, or disjunctive language. Code Civ.Proc., § 2030.060.', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(87, 1, 'Definitions are compound/conjunctive/disjunctive', 'Definitions are not prohibited from including compound, conjunctive, or disjunctive language. Code Civ.Proc., § 2031.030.', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(88, 1, 'Definitions are compound/conjunctive/disjunctive', 'Definitions are not prohibited from including compound, conjunctive, or disjunctive language. Code Civ.Proc., § 2033.060.', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(89, 1, 'Discovery is limited', 'Your &quot;discovery is limited&quot; objection fails because in the absence of privilege, the right to discovery in this state is a broad one, to be construed liberally so that parties may ascertain the strength of their case and at trial the truth may be determined. <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 538. &quot;Disclosure is a matter of right unless statutory or public policy considerations clearly prohibit it.&quot; <i>Id.</i> at 541.', '<b>Note</b>\r\n&quot;In the absence of privilege, the right to discovery in this state is a broad one, to be construed liberally so that parties may ascertain the strength of their case and at trial the truth may be determined. &quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 538.\r\n\r\n&quot;A trial court must be mindful of the Legislature&apos;s preference for discovery over trial by surprise, must construe the facts before it liberally in favor of discovery, may not use its discretion to extend the limits on discovery beyond those authorized by the Legislature, and should prefer partial to outright denials of discovery.&quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 540.\r\n\r\n&quot;Statutes governing discovery must be construed liberally in favor of disclosure unless the request is clearly improper by virtue of well-established causes for denial.&quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 541.\r\n\r\n&quot;Disclosure is a matter of right unless statutory or public policy considerations clearly prohibit it.&quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 541.', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(90, 1, 'Documents not categorized by Request number', 'Documents produced in response to a Request for Production &quot;shall be identified with the specific request number to which the documents respond.&quot; Code Civ. Proc., § 2031.280(a).', NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(91, 1, 'Duplicative of other discovery', 'A party may use multiple discovery methods (based upon different statutes) for obtaining the same documents or information. <i>Carter v. Superior Court</i> (1990) 218 Cal.App.3d 994, 997.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(92, 1, 'Equally available', '&quot;Equally available to the propounding party&quot; is only proper where the responding party does not have personal knowledge sufficient to respond fully to an interrogatory. Code Civ.Proc., § 2030.220(c). Since you&apos;ve failed to state that the respondent lacks sufficient personal knowledge, your objection is invalid. ', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(93, 1, 'Failure to detail objection', 'A Motion to Compel is warranted where an objection is &quot;too general.&quot; Code Civ. Proc., &sect; 2031.310.', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(94, 1, 'Failure to detail objection', 'Your objection is invalid because it fails to provide the requisite specificity. If an objection is made to an interrogatory or to a part of an interrogatory, the specific ground for the objection shall be set forth clearly in the response. If an objection is based on a claim of privilege, the particular privilege invoked shall be clearly stated. If an objection is based on a claim that the information sought is protected work product under Chapter 4 (commencing with Section 2018.010), that claim shall be expressly asserted. Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2030.240, subd. (b).', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(95, 1, 'Failure to identify responsive documents', 'Your response is insufficient because it fails to identify the documents responsive to each Request. &quot;Any documents or category of documents produced in response to a demand ... shall be identified with the specific request number to which the documents respond.&quot; Code Civ.Proc., § 2031.280, subd. (a).', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(96, 1, 'Fishing expedition', 'Your &quot;fishing expedition&quot; objection is invalid because discovery rules &quot;are applied liberally in favor of discovery, and (contrary to popular belief), fishing expeditions are permissible in some cases.&quot; <i>Stewart v. Colonial Western Agency, Inc.</i> (2001) 87 Cal.App.4th 1006, 1013, internal citations omitted.', '', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(97, 1, 'General objections', 'Your General Objections are meritless because objections must be specific, and &quot;boilerplate&quot; and &quot;nuisance&quot; objections are inappropriate. <i>Korea Data Systems Co. Ltd. v. Superior Court</i> (1997) 51 Cal.App.4th 1513, 1516.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, the responding party has the burden to justify its objections. Weil & Brown, Cal. Practice Guide&#58; Civil Procedure Before Trial (The Rutter Group 2021) &sect; 8:1179, citing <i>Coy v. Sup.Ct. (1962) 58 C2d 210, 220-221</i> and <i>Fairmont Ins. Co. v. Sup.Ct.</i> (2000) 22 C4th 245, 255.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(98, 1, 'Good cause required', '&quot;The statutory scheme imposes no obligation on a party propounding interrogatories to establish good cause or prove up the merits of any underlying claims.&quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 550, citing Code Civ. Proc., §§ 2017.010, 2030.010-2030.310.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(99, 1, 'Harassing', '&quot;Harrassing&quot; is not an approved objection to a Request for Admission. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019) &sect; 22.30.', NULL, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(100, 1, 'Harassing', '&quot;Harrassing&quot; is not an approved objection to an Interrogatory. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery &sect; 18.35.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(101, 1, 'Harrassing', '&quot;Harrassing&quot; is not an approved objection to a Request for Production or Inspection. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2020) § 19.30.', NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(102, 1, 'Incomplete hypothetical', '&quot;Incomplete hypothetical&quot; is not an approved objection to a Request for Admission. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019) &sect; 22.30.', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(103, 1, 'Incomplete hypothetical', '&quot;Incomplete hypothetical&quot; is not an approved objection to a Request for Production of Documents. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019) &sect; 19.30.', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(104, 1, 'Incomplete hypothetical', '&quot;Incomplete hypothetical&quot; is not an approved objection to an Interrogatory. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019) &sect; 18.35.', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(105, 1, 'Incomplete response', 'A Motion to compel further responses is proper when &quot;An answer to a particular interrogatory is evasive or incomplete.&quot; Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2030.300, subd. (a)(1).', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(106, 1, 'Insurance information', 'Evidence of insurance is discoverable and an employee has a right to an actual copy of the employer&apos;s insurance policy. <i>Irvington-Moore, Inc. v. Superior Court</i> (1993) 14 Cal.App.4th 733, 739-741. See also, <i>Laddon v. Superior Court In and For City and County of San Francisco</i> (1959) 167 Cal.App.2d 391, 394-95 [the &quot;existence and extent of liability insurance&quot; is discoverable.]', '', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(107, 1, 'Interrogatory refers to another interrogatory', 'Your objection that this Interrogatory &quot;refers to another Interrogatory&quot; is invalid because it doesn&apos;t require the respondent to go to materials outside the interrogatories. <i>Clement v. Alegre</i> (2009) 177 Cal.App.4th 1277, 1290.', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(108, 1, 'Interrogatory refers to another interrogatory in the set', 'The requirement that each Interrogatory be &quot;full and complete in and of itself&quot; is only violated it requires the respondent to resort to &quot;other materials&quot; in order to answer the question. Weil & Brown, Cal. Practice Guide&#58; Civil Procedure Before Trial (Ch. 8F-3 Interrogatories) The Rutter Group 2021 &sect; 8:979.5, citing <i>Catanese v. Sup.Ct.</i> (1996) 46 CA4th 1159, 1164.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(109, 1, 'Lack of/insufficient foundation', '&quot;Lack of or insufficient foundation&quot; is not a valid objection to a Request for Admission. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019) &sect; 22.30.', NULL, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(110, 1, 'Lack of/insufficient foundation', '&quot;Lack of or insufficient foundation&quot; is not a valid objection to an Interrogatory. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (September 2019) § 18.36.', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(111, 1, 'Necessitates compilation/summary', 'Your objection that the interrogatory necessitates &quot;the preparation or the making of a compilation, audit, or summary of documents&quot; is invalid. Even if you were correct, you&apos;re not entitled to refuse to respond. Your sole remedy is to permit the propounding party to &quot;examine, audit, or inspect these documents and to make copies, compilations, abstracts, or summaries of them.&quot; Code Civ. Proc., § 2030.230.', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(112, 1, 'Necessitates preparation/compilation/summary of documents', 'Your objection that the Interrogatory necessitates &quot;the preparation or the making of a compilation, audit, or summary of documents&quot; is insufficient and evasive. Even if you&apos;re correct, you are not entitled to refuse to respond. Your sole remedy is to identify the documents and permit me to &quot;examine, audit, or inspect these documents and to make copies, compilations, abstracts, or summaries of them.&quot; Code Civ. Proc., § 2030.230.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(113, 1, 'No responsive documents (without details)', 'Your response is not code-compliant because it fails to specify whether the inability to comply is because the particular item or category has never existed, has been destroyed, has been lost, misplaced, or stolen, or has never been, or is no longer, in the possession, custody, or control of the responding party. It&apos;s also required to set forth the name and address of any natural person or organization known or believed by that party to have possession, custody, or control of that item or category of item. Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2031.230', NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(114, 1, 'No responsive documents without explanation', 'Your response is insufficient because it fails to specify whether the inability to comply is because the particular item or category has never existed, has been destroyed, has been lost, misplaced, or stolen, or has never been, or is no longer, in the possession, custody, or control of the responding party. You&apos;re also required to set forth the name and address of any natural person or organization known or believed by that party to have possession, custody, or control of that item or category of item. Code Civ.Proc., § 2031.230.', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(115, 1, 'No. 12.3 - Refusal to respond (<i>Nacht</i>) ', '<i>Nacht & Lewis Architects, Inc. v. Superior Court</i> (1996) 47 Cal.App.4th 214, is limited to Form Interrogatory No. 12.2, which asks for the names of witnesses from whom statements have been obtained. It held that a list of witnesses from whom counsel took recorded statements at his or her own initiative constituted qualified work product &quot;because it would tend to reveal counsel&apos;s evaluation of the case by identifying the persons who claimed knowledge of the facts from whom counsel deemed it important to obtain statements.&quot; <i>McVeigh v. Recology San Francisco</i> (2013) 213 Cal.App.4th 443, 474.', NULL, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0),
	(116, 1, 'No. 15.1 - Insufficient response', 'Respondent&apos;s refusal to provide meaningful information about their affirmative defenses is in derogation of the Discovery Act by which &quot;the Legislature intended to take the &apos;game&apos; element out of trial preparation. … One of the principal purposes of discovery was to do away &apos;with the sporting theory of litigation namely, surprise at trial.&apos; … the phrase that discovery tends to &apos;make a trial less a game of blindman’s bluff and more a fair contest with the basic issues and facts disclosed to the fullest possible extent.&apos;&quot; <i>Greyhound Corp. v. Superior Court In and For Merced County (1961)</i> 56 Cal.2d 355, 376, internal citations omitted. Disclosure about each side&apos;s claims and defenses is necessary in order to prepare for settlement or trial. If the defendant  has strong, defensible affirmative defenses, the plaintiff may demand less to settle the case. Conversely, if the defendant lacks defensible affirmative defenses, as it appears, the plaintiff may demand more. Either way, the Discovery Act requires the parties to disclose facts &quot;to the fullest possible extent.&quot; Respondent&apos;s refusal to do so, in an effort to surprise plaintiff with the facts at trial, is in bad faith as well as in derogation of the law.', NULL, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0),
	(117, 1, 'No. 216.1 - Insufficient response', 'Respondent&apos;s refusal to provide meaningful information about their affirmative defenses is in derogation of the Discovery Act by which &quot;the Legislature intended to take the &apos;game&apos; element out of trial preparation. … One of the principal purposes of discovery was to do away &apos;with the sporting theory of litigation namely, surprise at trial.&apos; … the phrase that discovery tends to &apos;make a trial less a game of blindman’s bluff and more a fair contest with the basic issues and facts disclosed to the fullest possible extent.&apos;&quot; <i>Greyhound Corp. v. Superior Court In and For Merced County (1961)</i> 56 Cal.2d 355, 376, internal citations omitted. Disclosure about each side&apos;s claims and defenses is necessary in order to prepare for settlement or trial. If the defendant  has strong, defensible affirmative defenses, the plaintiff may demand less to settle the case. Conversely, if the defendant lacks defensible affirmative defenses, as it appears, the plaintiff may demand more. Either way, the Discovery Act requires the parties to disclose facts &quot;to the fullest possible extent.&quot; Respondent&apos;s refusal to do so, in an effort to surprise plaintiff with the facts at trial, is in bad faith as well as in derogation of the law.', NULL, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0),
	(118, 1, 'Non-specific objection', 'Merely citing the names of objections, without specifying the text objected to or the bases for the objection, renders them invalid as a matter of law. A motion to compel lies where objections are &quot;too general.&quot; Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2030.300(a)(3). See also, <i>Korea Data Systems Co. Ltd. v. Sup.Ct.</i> (1997) 51 CA4th 1513, 1516 [objecting party subject to sanctions for &quot;boilerplate&quot; objections].', '', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(119, 1, 'Not full and complete within itself', '&quot;Request is not full and complete within itself&quot; is a not an approved objection to a Request for Production of Documents. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery &sect; 19.30.', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(120, 1, 'Objection to Form Interrogatory', 'Judicial Council forms, like the one you&apos;re refusing to respond to, are presumptively valid. Gov. Code, &sect; 68511; Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2033.710.\r\n', '', 1, 1, 0, 0, 0),
	(121, 1, 'Oppressive', '&quot;Oppressive&quot; is not a valid objection because &quot;to support an objection of oppression there must be some showing either of an intent to create an unreasonable burden or that the ultimate effect of the burden is incommensurate with the result sought.&quot; <i>West Pico Furniture Co. of Los Angeles v. Superior Court In and For Los Angeles County</i> (1961) 56 Cal.2d 407, 417. Since you&apos;ve failed to make such a showing, your objection is invalid.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(122, 1, 'Others have the information', 'Your response that others have the information is insufficient. &quot;In answering interrogatories, a party must furnish information available from sources under the party&apos;s control: &apos;[A party] cannot plead ignorance to information which can be obtained from sources under his control.&apos;&quot; Weil & Brown, Cal. Practice Guide&#58; Civil Procedure Before Trial (The Rutter Group 2018) &sect; 8:1054, citing <i>Deyo v. Kilbourne</i> (1978) 84 Cal.App.3d 771, 782.', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(123, 1, 'Others have the information', 'Your response that others have the information is insufficient. You are required to produce all documents or things in your &quot;possession, custody, or control.&quot; Code Civ. Proc., § 2031.220.', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(124, 1, 'Overbroad', '&quot;Overbroad&quot; is not a valid objection to a Request for Production of Documents. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2020) &sect; 19.30.', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(125, 1, 'Overbroad', '&quot;Overbroad&quot; is not a valid objection to an Interrogatory. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery &sect; 18.35.', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(126, 1, 'Overbroad', '&quot;Overbroad&quot; is not a valid to objection to a Request for Admission. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery &sect; 22.30.', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(127, 1, 'Phrase not defined', '&quot;Phrase not defined&quot; is not an approved objection to a Request for Admission. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery &sect; 22.30.', '<b>Note</b>\r\n&quot;Phrase not defined&quot; is not an approved objection to a Request for Admission. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery &sect; 22.30.', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(128, 1, 'Phrase not defined', '&quot;Phrase not defined&quot; is not an approved objection to a Request for Production of Documents. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery &sect; 19.30.', '<b>Note</b>\r\n&quot;Phrase not defined&quot; is not an approved objection to a Request for Production of Documents. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery &sect; 19.30.', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(129, 1, 'Phrase not defined', '&quot;Phrase not defined&quot; is not an approved objection to an Interrogatory. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery &sect; 18.35.', '<b>Note</b>\r\n&quot;Phrase not defined&quot; is not an approved objection to an Interrogatory. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery &sect; 18.35.', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(130, 1, 'Prior discovery must be completed first', 'Your objection that other discovery must be completed first is invalid. &quot;Except as otherwise provided by a rule of the Judicial Council, a local court rule, or a local uniform written policy, the methods of discovery may be used in any sequence, and the fact that a party is conducting discovery, whether by deposition or another method, shall not operate to delay the discovery of any other party.&quot; Code Civ. Proc., § 2019.020(a).', NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
	(131, 1, 'Privacy', 'Your privacy analysis is incomplete. While you&apos;re correct that informational privacy is Constitutionally protected, that&apos;s merely the beginning of the analysis, not the end. As the California Supreme Court explained, &quot;The party asserting a privacy right must establish a legally protected privacy interest, an objectively reasonable expectation of privacy in the given circumstances, and a threatened intrusion that is serious.&quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 552. Since you&apos;ve failed to establish &quot;a threatened intrusion that is serious,&quot; your privacy objection is invalid.', '<b>Note</b>\r\nYour privacy analysis is incomplete. While you&apos;re correct that informational privacy is Constitutionally protected, that&apos;s merely the beginning of the analysis, not the end. As the California Supreme Court explained, &quot;The party asserting a privacy right must establish a legally protected privacy interest, an objectively reasonable expectation of privacy in the given circumstances, and a threatened intrusion that is serious.&quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 552.\r\n\r\n<p>Additionally, privacy only protects a reasonable expectation of privacy &quot;against a serious invasion.&quot; <i>Pioneer Electronics (USA), Inc. v. Superior Court</i> (2007) 40 Cal.4th 360, 370. In the seminal case of <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, the California Supreme Court stated that, &quot;the party asserting a privacy right must establish a legally protected privacy interest, an objectively reasonable expectation of privacy in the given circumstances, and a threatened intrusion that is serious.&quot; <i>Id.</i> at 552. Since you&apos;ve failed to establish &quot;a threatened intrusion that is serious,&quot; your privacy objection is invalid.\r\n\r\n<p>I&apos;ll concede that the privacy interests at stake are both legally protected and objectively reasonable. However, disclosure of contact information is not a &quot;serious&quot; intrusion, as a matter of law. &quot;Nor was any prospective invasion of privacy serious: &apos;the information, while personal, was not particularly sensitive, as it was contact information, not medical or financial details.&apos;&quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 553. See also, <i>Puerto v. Superior Court</i> (2008) 158 Cal.App.4th 1242, 1249-1250 [&quot;Central to the discovery process is the identification of potential witnesses. &apos;The disclosure of the names and addresses of potential witnesses is a routine and essential part of pretrial discovery.&apos;&quot;] \r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Our discovery system is founded on the understanding that parties use discovery to obtain names and contact information for possible witnesses as the starting point for further investigations.&quot; <i>Puerto v. Superior Court</i> (2008) 158 Cal.App.4th 1242, 1250. We use services such as intellius.com and spokeo.com to research witnesses, looking for felony convictions, bias, interest, associations with other witnesses or parties, and any other information that might be useful in preparing his case for settlement or trial. The witnesses&apos; addresses and telephone numbers are necessary because there are many people with similar names.\r\n\r\n<p>The Discovery Act, Code of Civil Procedure section 2017.010, entitles me to &quot;the identity and location of persons having knowledge of any discoverable matter,&quot; e.g. percipient witnesses. And the Rutter Guide agrees: &quot;Although disclosure may invade their privacy, there is generally no protection for the identity, addresses and phone numbers of percipient witnesses.&quot; Weil & Brown, Cal. Practice Guide&#58; Civil Procedure Before Trial (The Rutter Group 2020) &#182; 8:299.5. \r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Discovery may be obtained of the identity and location of persons having knowledge of any discoverable matter.&quot; Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2017.010.\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;<b>home</b> addresses and telephone numbers [are] routinely produced during discovery.&quot; <i>Planned Parenthood Golden Gate v. Superior Court</i> (2000) 83 Cal.App.4th 347, 359, disapproved of on other grounds by <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, emphasis added. See also, <i>Puerto v. Superior Court</i> (2008) 158 Cal.App.4th 1242, 1254 [&quot;it is only under unusual circumstances that the courts restrict discovery of nonparty witnesses <b>residential</b> contact information.&quot; emphasis added.]\r\n\r\n<p>Your privacy objection is invalid because &quot;the constitutional right to privacy is not absolute. It may be outweighed by supervening concerns. The state has enough of an interest in discovering the truth in legal proceedings, that it may compel disclosure of confidential material.&quot; <i>Doe 2 v. Superior Court</i> (2005) 132 Cal.App.4th 1504, internal citations omitted. The State of California expressed its interest in discovery the truth by enacting the Discovery Act, Code of Civil Procedure, section 2017.010, which entitles me to &quot;discovery regarding any matter, not privileged, that is relevant to the subject matter involved.&quot;\r\n\r\n<p><b>Compelling Interest Not Required</b>\r\nNot all privacy interests under article I, section 1 must be overcome by a &quot;compelling interest.&quot; <i>Hill v. National Collegiate Athletic Assn.</i> (1994) 7 Cal.4th 1, 34-35.', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(132, 1, 'Privacy&#58; Balancing test required', 'Your objection that a &quot;balancing test&quot; is invalid because no balancing test is required, as a matter of law. In <i>Hill v. National Collegiate Athletic Assn.</i> (1994) 7 Cal.4th 1, 35-37, the California Supreme Court established a three part test for privacy protection: 1) a legally protected privacy interest&#59; 2) a reasonable expectation of privacy&#59; and 3) the discovery must create a serious invasion of privacy. In <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 555, the California Supreme Court ruled that unless all three threshold Hill requirements are met, no balancing test is required. Since you haven&apos;t established that this discovery constitutes a &quot;serious invasion,&quot; no balancing test is required,  as a matter of law.', '<b>Notes</b>\r\nNo balancing test is required. In <i>Hill v. National Collegiate Athletic Assn.</i> (1994) 7 Cal.4th 1, 35-37, the California Supreme Court established a three part test for privacy protection: 1) a legally protected privacy interest&#59; 2) a reasonable expectation of privacy&#59; and 3) the discovery must create a serious invasion of privacy. In <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 555, the California Supreme Court ruled that unless all three threshold <i>Hill</i> requirements are met, no balancing test is required. Since you haven&apos;t established that this discovery constitutes a serious invasion, no balancing test is required,  as a matter of law.', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(133, 1, 'Privacy&#58; Compelling interest/need required', 'Your objection that a &quot;compelling interest or need&quot; is required is invalid because, in <i>Hill v. National Collegiate Athletic Assn.</i> (1994) 7 Cal.4th 1, 35-37, the California Supreme Court established a three part test for privacy protection&#58; 1) a legally protected privacy interest&#59; 2) a reasonable expectation of privacy&#59; and 3) the discovery must create a serious invasion of privacy. In <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 557, the California Supreme Court ruled that unless all three threshold Hill requirements are met, no compelling interest or need is required. Since you&apos;ve failed to meet all the <i>Hill</i> requirements, no compelling interest or need is required.', '\r\n', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(134, 1, 'Privacy&#58; Employee records', 'The EEOC has specifically warned employers not to promise complete confidentiality to witnesses in workplace investigations. (June 16, 1999, EEOC Notice 915.002).', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(135, 1, 'Privacy&#58; Financial information (Code Civ.Proc. &sect; 3295', 'Your objection that this discovery violates \r\nCode of Civil Procedure, section 3295 is invalid because that statute only prohibits inquiries into &quot;(1) The profits the defendant has gained by virtue of the wrongful course of conduct of the nature and type shown by the evidence. (2) The financial condition of the defendant.&quot; Since this discovery doesn&apos;t intrude into those areas, it is not prohibited.', '<b>Note</b>\r\nCode of Civil Procedure, section 3295 only prohibits inquiries into &quot;(1) The profits the defendant has gained by virtue of the wrongful course of conduct of the nature and type shown by the evidence. (2) The financial condition of the defendant.&quot; Since this discovery doesn&apos;t intrude into those areas, it is not prohibited.', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(136, 1, 'Privacy&#58; Student records (FERPA)', 'Your objection that The Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA) precludes release of this information fails because FERPA only prevents educational institutions from revealing students&apos; &quot;personally identifiable information.&quot; However, that only prevents the institutions from voluntarily doing so. &quot;An educational institution may release personally identifiable information contained in a student&apos;s records if the institution is subpoenaed.&quot; <i>Victory Outreach Center v. City of Philadelphia</i> (E.D. Pa. 2005) 233 F.R.D. 419, 420.', '<b>Note</b>\r\nThe Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA) prevents educational institutions from revealing students&apos; &quot;personally identifiable information.&quot; However, that only prevents the institutions from <i>voluntarily</i> doing so. &quot;An educational institution may release personally identifiable information contained in a student&apos;s records if the institution is subpoenaed.&quot; <i>Victory Outreach Center v. City of Philadelphia</i> (E.D. Pa. 2005) 233 F.R.D. 419, 420.', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(137, 1, 'Privacy&#58; Witness Contact Information', 'Your objection that witness contact information is protected by privacy rights is invalid because, even assuming that the privacy interest is both legally protected and objectively reasonable, disclosure of contact information is not a &quot;serious&quot; intrusion, as a matter of law. &quot;Nor was any prospective invasion of privacy serious: &apos;the information, while personal, was not particularly sensitive, as it was contact information, not medical or financial details.&apos;&quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court, supra,</i> 3 Cal.5th 531 at 553. See also, <i>Puerto v. Superior Court</i> (2008) 158 Cal.App.4th 1242, 1249-1250 [&quot;Central to the discovery process is the identification of potential witnesses. &apos;The disclosure of the names and addresses of potential witnesses is a routine and essential part of pretrial discovery.&quot;] And the Rutter Guide agrees&#58; [&quot;Although disclosure may invade their privacy, there is generally no protection for the identity, addresses and phone numbers of percipient witnesses.[&quot; Weil & Brown, Cal. Practice Guide: Civil Procedure Before Trial (The Rutter Group 2020) § 8:299.5.', '', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(138, 1, 'Proprietary', '&quot;Proprietary&quot; is not a valid objection to an interrogatory. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019) &sect; 18.35.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(139, 1, 'Protective Order', 'I will not agree to a protective order for two reasons&#58; First, because &quot;protective orders are disfavored. ... such agreements will not be recognized or approved ... absent a particularized showing (document by document) that&#58; (a) Secrecy is in the public interest&#59; and (b) The proponent has a cognizable interest in the material ... or is otherwise protected by law from disclosure&#59; and (c) That disclosure would cause serious harm.&quot; <i>Stadish v. Superior Court</i> (1999) 71 Cal.App.4th 1130, 1147. Even if the Court considers such a deviation from established practice, your request will be denied because you&apos;ve failed to even argue&#8212;let alone demonstrate&#8212;that suppression of the document request is &quot;in the public interest&quot; and, if not prohibited, will &quot;cause serious harm&quot; as required for issuance of a protective order. Second, a protective order would only be warranted to protect someone &quot;from unwarranted annoyance, embarrassment, or oppression, or undue burden and expense.&quot; Code Civ. Proc., 2025.420, subd. (b). However, you&apos;ve failed to cite any &quot;annoyance, embarrassment, or oppression, or undue burden and expense&quot; imposed by the request. Furthermore, California puts the burden on the objecting party to demonstrate that the annoyance, embarrassment, etc. is unwarranted. &quot;Generally, a deponent seeking a protective order will be required to show that the burden, expense, or intrusiveness involved in ... [the discovery procedure] clearly outweighs the likelihood that the information sought will lead to the discovery of admissible evidence.&quot; Weil & Brown, Cal. Practice Guide&#58; Civil Procedure Before Trial (The Rutter Group 2020) &#182; 8:689, citing <i>Emerson Electric Co. v. Superior Court</i> (1997) 16 C4th 1101, 1110. Absent a showing that the document requests will cause &quot;annoyance, embarrassment, or oppression, or undue burden and expense&quot; that &quot;clearly outweighs whatever benefits are sought&quot; by the requests, there are no grounds upon which to grant a protective order.', '<b>Notes</b>\r\nAttorneys seeking to obstruct discovery frequently state that they&apos;ll only provide responsive information or documents if you stipulate to a Protective Order. Here&apos;s authority that you don&apos;t have to agree to one.\r\n\r\n', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(140, 1, 'Referencing documents in response', 'Your reference to other documents is improper because you failed to allege that 1) a compilation or summary of the documents is necessary to answer the interrogatory; 2) no such compilation presently exists; and 3) the burden or expense of preparing it would be substantially the same for the propounding party. Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2030.230. Even had you done so, your response would still be insufficient because you failed to specify the documents in sufficient detail to permit me to locate and identify them. <i>Ibid.</i>', '<b>Note</b>\r\nWhen a response to an Interrogatory involves preparation of a compilation or summary of documents, respondents may avoid it by identifying the documents and allowing the propounding party to review and copy them. Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2030.230. \r\n\r\nHowever, to avail themselves of this option, the respondent must state that 1) a compilation or summary of the documents is necessary to answer the interrogatory; 2) no such compilation presently exists; 3) the burden or expense of preparing it would be substantially the same for the propounding party; and 4) offer the propounding party a reasonable opportunity to examine and make copies of the documents. Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2030.230.\r\n\r\nYour reference to other documents is improper because you failed to allege that 1) a compilation or summary of the documents is necessary to answer the interrogatory; 2) no such compilation presently exists; and 3) the burden or expense of preparing it would be substantially the same for the propounding party. Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 2030.230. Even had you done so, your response would still be insufficient because you failed to specify the documents in sufficient detail to permit me to locate and identify them. <i>Ibid.</i>', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0),
	(141, 1, 'Relevance', 'Your &quot;relevance&quot; objection is invalid becuase, &quot;for discovery purposes, information is relevant if it &apos;might reasonably assist a party in evaluating the case, preparing for trial, or facilitating settlement....&apos; Admissibility is not the test and information unless privileged, is discoverable if it might reasonably lead to admissible evidence. These rules are applied liberally in favor of discovery, and (contrary to popular belief), fishing expeditions are permissible in some cases.&quot; <i>Stewart v. Colonial Western Agency, Inc.</i> (2001) 87 Cal.App.4th 1006, 1013, internal citations omitted.', '<b>Note</b>\r\n&quot;For discovery purposes, information is relevant if it &apos;might reasonably assist a party in evaluating the case, preparing for trial, or facilitating settlement....&apos; Admissibility is not the test and information unless privileged, is discoverable if it might reasonably lead to admissible evidence. These rules are applied liberally in favor of discovery, and (contrary to popular belief), fishing expeditions are permissible in some cases.&quot; <i>Stewart v. Colonial Western Agency, Inc.</i> (2001) 87 Cal.App.4th 1006, 1013, internal citations omitted.\r\n\r\nThe &quot;relevance to the subject matter&quot; and &quot;reasonably calculated to lead to discovery of admissible evidence&quot; standards are applied liberally. Any doubt is generally resolved in favor of permitting discovery, particularly where the precise issues in the case are not yet clearly established. Weil & Brown, Cal. Practice Guide: Civil Procedure Before Trial (The Rutter Group 2020) &#182; 8:71, citing <i>Colonial Life & Accident Ins. Co. v. Sup.Ct.</i> (1982) 31 C3d 785, 790, fns. 7-8.\r\n\r\n&quot;Statutes governing discovery must be construed liberally in favor of disclosure unless the request is clearly improper by virtue of well-established causes for denial.&quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 541.\r\n\r\n&quot;Disclosure is a matter of right unless statutory or public policy considerations clearly prohibit it.&quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 541.', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(142, 1, 'Request is not full and complete within itself', 'Your objection that the Request &quot;is not full and complete within itself&quot; is a not a valid objection to a Request for Production of Documents. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery § 19.30.', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1),
	(143, 1, 'Training', 'TRAINING refers to teaching or educating.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(144, 1, 'Unable to admit or deny', 'Your representation that the respondent is unable to admit or deny the Request is insufficient and evasive because the Discovery Act requires that the response be as complete and straightforward as the information reasonably available permits. Code Civ. Proc., § 2030(f)(1). See also, <i>Deyo v. Kilbourne</i> (1979) 84 Cal.App.3d 771, 782 [In answering interrogatories, a party must furnish information available from sources under the party’s control. &quot;A party cannot plead ignorance to information which can be obtained from sources under his control.&quot;]\r\n\r\nAdditionally, a respondent giving lack of information or knowledge as a reason for their inability to admit or deny, &quot;shall state in the answer that a reasonable inquiry concerning the matter in the particular request has been made, and that the information known or readily obtainable is insufficient to enable that party to admit the matter. &quot; Code Civ. Proc., § 2033.220. Furthermore, a respondent’s simple statement that they made a &quot;reasonable&quot; inquiry may not be sufficient. The propounding party may move to compel a proper response or to have the matter ordered admitted if the respondent hasn&apos;t made a reasonable inquiry or has access to &quot;readily available&quot; information that would enable them to admit or deny the matter. <i>Asea, Inc. v. Southern Pac. Transp. Co.</i> (9th Cir. 1981) 669 F2d 1242, 1245-1246 (decided under analogous FRCP rule).', NULL, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(145, 1, 'Unable to fully respond', 'Your representation that the respondent is unable to fully response is legally insufficient. If the responding party lacks personal knowledge sufficient to respond, he or she may so state, but only after making a reasonable and good faith effort to obtain the information by inquiry to other persons or organizations. <i>Sinaiko Healthcare Consulting, Inc. v. Pacific Healthcare Consultants</i> (2007) 148 CA4th 390, 406.', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 1),
	(146, 1, 'Unverified responses', 'Unverified responses &quot;are tantamount to no responses at all.&quot; <i>Appleton v. Superior Court</i> (1988) 206 Cal.App.3d 632.', '<b>Notes:</b>\r\nThis does not apply to responses consisting solely of objections.', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(147, 1, 'Vague', '&quot;Vague&quot; is not an approved objection to a Request for Admission. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019) &sect; 22.30.', '<b>Note</b>\r\n&quot;Vague&quot; is not an approved objection to a Request for Admission. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019) &sect; 22.30.', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0),
	(148, 1, 'Vague/ambiguous', '&quot;Vague&quot; and &quot;ambiguous&quot; are &quot;nuisance&quot; objections and a party relying upon them, as you&apos;ve done, is &quot;subject to sanction.&quot; <i>Standon Co. v. Superior Court</i> (1990) 225 Cal.App.3d 898, 901.', '', 1, 1, 1, 0, 1),
	(149, 1, 'Vague/ambiguous/unintelligible', '&quot;Vague,&quot; &quot;ambiguous,&quot; and &quot;unintelligible&quot; are nuisance objections and a party relying upon them, as you&apos;ve done, is &quot;subject to sanction.&quot; <i>Standon Co. v. Superior Court</i> (1990) 225 Cal.App.3d 898, 901.', '', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),
	(150, 1, 'Verification based upon information and belief', 'A verification based upon &quot;information and belief&quot; is insufficient. Weil & Brown, Cal. Practice Guide&#58; Civil Procedure Before Trial (Ch. 8F-3 Interrogatories) The Rutter Group 2021 &#182; 8:1104, citing Code Civ.Proc., &sect; 446.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1),

	(151, 2, 'Abusive', 'ABUSIVE means extremely offensive and insulting.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(152, 2, 'Accommodate/Accommodation', 'ACCOMMODATE means to provide a modification or adjustment to the workplace that enables the employee or applicant to perform the essential functions of the job. Such a modification or adjustment is an ACCOMMODATION.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(153, 2, 'Action', 'ACTION means doing something.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(154, 2, 'Adverse Employment Action', 'ADVERSE EMPLOYMENT ACTION means an action that materially affects the terms and conditions of employment, including  termination, suspension, demotion, reprimand, loss of pay, failure or refusal to hire, failure or refusal to promote, or any other action or failure to act that adversely affects the employee&apos;s rights or interests.', 'Gov. Code &sect; 12940.', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(155, 2, 'Cite Documents', 'CITE DOCUMENTS means to list all DOCUMENTS, sufficiently that they can be identified in a Request for Production of Documents. DOCUMENT means a writing, as defined in Evidence Code section 250, and includes the original or a copy of handwriting, typewriting, printing, photocopies, photographing, and every other means of recording upon any tangible thing and form of communicating or representation, including letters, words, pictures, sounds, or symbols, or combinations of them.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(156, 2, 'Communication', 'COMMUNICATION means any and all types of communication, including voice, paper, email, text, and all other forms of communication, regardless of whether the information was received or acknowledged.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(157, 2, 'Complain', 'COMPLAIN mean a COMMUNICATION that something is unsatisfactory, unacceptable, improper, or illegal. COMMUNICATION means any and all types of communication, including voice, paper, email, text, and all other forms of communication, regardless of whether the information was received or acknowledged.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(158, 2, 'Complaint', 'COMPLAINT means the complaint filed by the plaintiff in this action.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(159, 2, 'Constructive Termination', 'CONSTRUCTIVE TERMINATION refers to a situation where, looking at the totality of circumstances, a reasonable person in the employee&apos;s position would have felt that they were forced to quit because of intolerable working conditions.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(160, 2, 'Contact Information', 'CONTACT INFORMATION refers to the person&apos;s full name, last-known residential address, last-known residential phone number, and if the person is currently employed by respondent.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(161, 2, 'Custodian', 'CUSTODIAN means a natural person or business that keeps and/or retains DOCUMENTS on behalf of a natural person or business. DOCUMENT means a writing, as defined in Evidence Code section 250, and includes the original or a copy of handwriting, typewriting, printing, photocopies, photographing, and every other means of recording upon any tangible thing and form of communicating or representation, including letters, words, pictures, sounds, or symbols, or combinations of them.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(162, 2, 'Disability/Disabled', 'A DISABILITY is a physical or mental condition that limits a major life activity&#59; it may be actual or perceived by the employer. A person with a current DISABILITY is DISABLED.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(163, 2, 'Discipline/Disciplinary Action', 'DISCIPLINE or DISCIPLINARY ACTION mean actions including but not limited to, a warning or admonishment, whether oral or written, any reduction in rank, seniority, job duties, schedule changes, title, benefits, or pay, suspension, or termination.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(164, 2, 'Discriminate/Discrimination/Discriminatory', 'DISCRIMINATE, DISCRIMINATION, and DISCRIMINATORY refer to treating people differently based upon characteristics including but not limited to their race, gender, age, medical condition, or sexual orientation.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(165, 2, 'Document', 'DOCUMENT means a writing, as defined in Evidence Code section 250, and includes the original or a copy of handwriting, typewriting, printing, photocopies, photographing, and every other means of recording upon any tangible thing and form of communicating or representation, including letters, words, pictures, sounds, or symbols, or combinations of them.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(166, 2, 'Duty/Duties', 'DUTY or DUTIES are the work that needs to be performed in a role and the functions that an employee is accountable for.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(167, 2, 'Harass/Harassing/Harassment', 'HARASS, HARASSING, or HARASSMENT refer to verbal conduct such as making epithets, derogatory comments or slurs, romantic overtures, sexual comments and/or jokes, and prying into one&apos;s personal affairs; physical conduct such as unwanted touching, rubbing against someone, assault, and physical interference with movement or work; and visual conduct such as derogatory cartoons, drawings or posters, and lewd gestures or LEERING. LEER means to look or gaze in an unpleasant, malicious, or lascivious way.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(168, 2, 'Hostile Work Environment', 'HOSTILE WORK ENVIRONMENT refers to inappropriate behavior in the workplace that is either severe or pervasive enough to create an ABUSIVE work atmosphere for one or more employees. ABUSIVE means extremely offensive and insulting.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(169, 2, 'Humiliate/Humiliation', 'HUMILIATE or HUMILIATION mean to make someone feel ashamed and foolish by injuring their dignity and self-respect, especially publicly.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(170, 2, 'Identity/Identify/Identification', 'IDENTITY, IDENTIFY, or IDENTIFICATION means to provide the person&apos;s full name, last-known residential address, last-known residential phone number, and if the person is currently employed by respondent. ', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(171, 2, 'Interactive Process', 'INTERACTIVE PROCESS means an employer&apos;s timely, good faith, communication with the employee or applicant to determine effective reasonable ACCOMMODATIONS, if any, in response to either 1) a request for a reasonable ACCOMMODATION&#59; or 2) the employer&apos;s knowledge of the employee&apos;s or applicant&apos;s medical condition. ACCOMMODATION means a modification or adjustment to the workplace that enables the employee to perform the essential functions of the job. ACCOMMODATE means to provide an ACCOMMODATION.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(172, 2, 'Investigation', 'INVESTIGATION means an inquiry for the purpose of ascertaining facts.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(173, 2, 'Joint Employers', 'JOINT EMPLOYERS refer to multiple business entities who share control and supervision of an employee&apos;s activity.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(174, 2, 'Leer', 'LEER means to look or gaze in an unpleasant, malicious, or lascivious way.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(175, 2, 'List', 'LIST means to state the date of the statement, contents of the statement, IDENTITY of everyone who witnessed the statement, and whether the plaintiff was present. IDENTITY, IDENTIFY, or IDENTIFICATION means to provide the person&apos;s full name, last-known residential address, last-known residential phone number, and if the person is currently employed by respondent.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 0),
	(176, 2, 'Managing Agent', 'MANAGING AGENT refers to an employee with discretionary authority over decisions that ultimately determine corporate policy, including the authority to hire and fire employees.', NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
	(177, 2, 'Mistreated/Mistreatment', 'MISTREATED or MISTREATMENT refers to bad, cruel, or unfair treatment.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(178, 2, 'National Origin', 'NATIONAL ORIGIN means ancestry, race, and/or national origin.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(179, 2, 'Negative', 'NEGATIVE means focused on what is bad or lacking.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(180, 2, 'Participate/Participation ', 'PARTICIPATE and PARTICIPATION mean to take part in, engage in, play a part or roll in, have a hand in, assist in, be a participant in, help out with, assist in, contribute to, partake, or be associated with.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(181, 2, 'Person', 'PERSON means any natural person, firm, association, organization, partnership, business, trust, corporation, limited liability company, joint venture or public entity.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(182, 2, 'Personnel File', 'PERSONNEL FILE means information about the employee including, but not limited to, DISCIPLINARY ACTIONS, attendance, requests for promotion, promotions, demotions, work assignments, SUPERVISORS&apos; comments and reviews, performance improvement plans, hours worked, certifications, notification of disabilities (whether for the employee himself or others), and accrued time off. DISCIPLINE or DISCIPLINARY ACTION mean actions including but not limited to, a warning or admonishment, whether oral or written, any reduction in rank, seniority, job duties, schedule changes, title, benefits, or pay, suspension, or termination. SUPERVISOR means an employee who manages, supervises, or controls the work or activities of other employees in any way.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(183, 2, 'Policy', 'A POLICY means the way respondent interacts with and DISCIPLINES its employees, including but not limited to policies, procedures, handbooks, guidelines, and rules. DISCIPLINE or DISCIPLINARY ACTION mean actions including but not limited to, a warning or admonishment, whether oral or written, any reduction in rank, seniority, job duties, schedule changes, title, benefits, or pay, suspension, or termination.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(184, 2, 'Positive', 'POSITIVE means marked by or indicating acceptance, approval, or affirmation.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(185, 2, 'Progressive Discipline', 'PROGRESSIVE DISCIPLINE refers to the process of using increasingly severe steps or measures when an employee fails to correct a problem after being given a reasonable opportunity to do so.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(186, 2, 'Promotion', 'PROMOTION means being raised in position or rank.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(187, 2, 'Proper Meal Break', 'PROPER MEAL BREAK mean a meal break at least 30 minutes long&#59; uninterrupted by any work&#59; where the employee was free to leave the premises&#59; and which began no later than the end of the employee&apos;s fifth hour of work.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(188, 2, 'Proper Rest Break', 'PROPER REST BREAK means a rest break at least 10 minutes long&#59; uninterrupted by any work&#59; occurring every 4 hours, or major fraction thereof, of work&#59; and where a good faith effort was made to provide the break in the middle of the work period.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(189, 2, 'Ratify/Ratification', 'RATIFY and RATIFICATION refer to adoption or enactment.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(190, 2, 'Reckless Disregard', 'RECKLESS DISREGARD means either 1) Conscious indifference to the consequences of an act&#59; or 2) Serious indifference to truth or accuracy of a publication. Black&apos;s Law Dictionary (11th ed. 2019).', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(191, 2, 'Related To', 'RELATED TO means referencing or referring to in any way, whether expressly or impliedly.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(192, 2, 'Retaliate/Retaliation', 'RETALIATE or RETALIATION means an ADVERSE EMPLOYMENT ACTION taken because an employee  engaged in a legally protected activity. ADVERSE EMPLOYMENT ACTION means an action that materially affects the terms and conditions of employment, including termination, suspension, demotion, reprimand, loss of pay, failure or refusal to hire, failure or refusal to promote, or any other action or failure to act that adversely affects the employee&apos;s rights or interests.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(193, 2, 'Serious Health Condition', 'A SERIOUS HEALTH CONDITION means an illness, injury, impairment or physical or mental condition that involves inpatient care or continuing treatment by a health care provider.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(194, 2, 'Severe Emotional Distress', 'SEVERE EMOTIONAL DISTRESS means emotional distress of such substantial quality or enduring quality that no reasonable person in civilized society should be expected to endure it.', '<i>Potter v. Firestone Tire & Rubber Co.</i> (1993) 6 Cal.4th 965, 1004.', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(195, 2, 'Supervisor', 'SUPERVISOR means an employee who manages, supervises, or controls the work or activities of other employees in any way.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(196, 2, 'Undue Hardship', 'UNDUE HARDSHIP means an action requiring significant difficulty or expense, when considered in light of (1) The nature and cost of the ACCOMMODATION&#59; (2) The anticipated financial resources involved in the provision of the ACCOMMODATION, the number of employees at the facility where the employee worked, and the effect on expenses and resources or the impact of the ACCOMMODATION upon the operation of the facility&#59; (3) the employer&apos;s overall financial resources, the number of employees affected, and the number, type, and location of the facility where the employee works or worked&#59; (4) The type of operations of the employer&apos;s workforce&#59; and (5) The geographic separateness or administrative or fiscal relationship of the facility where the employee worked. ACCOMMODATION means a modification or adjustment to the workplace that enables the employee to perform the essential functions of the job. ACCOMMODATE means to provide an ACCOMMODATION.', NULL, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
	(197, 2, 'You/Your', 'YOU and YOUR means respondent or any of YOUR agents, representatives, affiliated entities or anyone acting or whom YOU know or believe is purporting to act on YOUR behalf or who has acted or whom YOU know or believe is purporting to act on YOUR behalf.', '', 0, 0, 1, 1, 1);

